## Required: Use ABP Skills before ABP-specific work

Invoke the relevant `abp-*` Skill BEFORE the corresponding work.

| Work area | Skill |
|---|---|
| Application services, DTOs, Mapperly, CRUD | `abp-application-layer` |
| Angular UI components, guards, proxies, interceptors | `abp-angular` |
| Domain entities, aggregates, repositories | `abp-ddd` |
| EF Core repositories, migrations, seeders | `abp-ef-core` |
| ABP CLI commands (generate-proxy, install-libs, etc.) | `abp-cli` |
| Permissions, `[Authorize]`, `IsGrantedAsync` | `abp-authorization` |
| Settings, FeatureChecker, distributed cache, background jobs | `abp-infrastructure` |
| Anything else ABP, or unsure | `abp-core` |

If a Skill doesn't cover a specific question, fetch version-pinned docs:
`https://docs.abp.io/en/abp/latest/...`

**ABP standards win over local patterns.** Drift is technical debt — prefer
the ABP-standard approach for new code and flag legacy patterns in the PR.

## Required: Never hand-edit generated files

Always regenerate via the tool when the source changes. Applies to:

{{#if ui_angular}}
- `angular/src/app/proxy/**` — regenerate with:
  ```bash
  cd angular && abp generate-proxy -t ng -m app -url https://localhost:44326 -o src/app/proxy
  ```
{{/if}}
{{#if ui_mvc}}
- `wwwroot/libs/` — installed by `abp install-libs`.
{{/if}}
{{#if ui_blazor_server}}
- `wwwroot/libs/` — installed by `abp install-libs`.
{{/if}}
{{#if db_ef}}
- EF Core `Designer.cs` / `*ModelSnapshot.cs` files — managed by `dotnet ef`.
{{/if}}

If code-review bots flag these files, the only valid fix paths are:
1. Fix the **source** and regenerate.
2. If it's a generator quirk with no actionable source change, acknowledge and skip.

## Required: After IdentityUserManager updates, don't trust _userRepository.GetAsync

When you update an `IdentityUser` via `IdentityUserManager` methods (`SetEmailAsync`,
`SetUserNameAsync`, etc.), a subsequent `_userRepository.GetAsync(userId)` may return
the EF-tracked entity **without those changes** — the Identity stores write through
their own path. This bug surfaces in **PostgreSQL but NOT in the SQLite in-memory
test fixture**, so integration tests pass while production is wrong.

Map from the in-memory variable you just modified, not from a fresh repository read:

```csharp
var user = await _userManager.GetByIdAsync(profile.UserId);
CheckIdentityResult(await _userManager.SetEmailAsync(user, input.Email));
CheckIdentityResult(await _userManager.UpdateAsync(user));
await uow.CompleteAsync();

// CORRECT: use the in-memory `user` (has the updates)
var reloaded = await _yourRepo.GetAsync(profile.Id);
return _mapper.FromEntity(reloaded, user);

// WRONG: returns stale email/username/phone in production
// var reloadedUser = await _userRepository.GetAsync(reloaded.UserId);
```

## Required: URL convention for current-user endpoints

User-self-scoped endpoints use `/me` (not `/my`). Place explicit
**absolute-path** `[Http*]` attributes on the **implementation method**
(interface attributes are silent decoration — MVC reads from the implementation
`MethodInfo`). Leading slash is required so the attribute appends to the
controller prefix rather than replacing it.

```csharp
[HttpGet("/api/app/account/me")]
public async Task<AccountDto?> GetMyAsync() { ... }

[HttpPut("/api/app/account/me/profile")]
public async Task<AccountDto> UpdateMyProfileAsync(...) { ... }
```

After backend route changes, regenerate the Angular proxy.

